th impairments from the workforce, disabled mineworkers were expected to return to work wherever possible, and new medical services developed to assist in this endeavour. This book explores the working lives of disabled miners and analyses the medical, welfare and community responses to disablement in the coalfields. It shows how disability affected industrial relations and shaped the class identity of mineworkers. The book will appeal to students and academics interested in disability, occupational health and social history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial sciences. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBritish coalmining.  aClass.  aCoalmining.  aCommunity.  aDisability.  aIndustrial Relations.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aWelfare.  aWork.  acoal economy.  acoalfield communities.  adisability studies.  aindustrial politics.  amedical responses.  amining families.  aphysical impairments.  asocial relations.  awelfare responses.1 aBlackie, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBlackie, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526125774zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125774zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125774/original  a978-3-11-128277-0 Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA